The University of Western Cape's Institute for Poverty, Land and Agrarian Studies said more emphasis needs to placed on urban land reform. Courtesy of #DSTV403 CAPE TOWN - More focus must be placed on urban land reform according to the University of Western Cape's Institute for Poverty, Land and Agrarian Studies (PLAAS). READ: Didiza meets with affected parties to quell land dispute The institute said the government should also relook at ways to ensure people have documented rights to the land they occupy.
Professor Ruth Hall said, "It's been a mistake that land reform has gravitated towards the rural only, even in the rural areas, a focus on farming and commercial farming." "I think there's a diversity of needs that are being largely ignored." READ: Land claimants vindicated by ConCourt ruling "Another important proposal is that 60 percent of <the> population does not have documents to <the> land they occupy, the system of private title only works for a minority." "Poor people remain vulnerable to lose property rights. We need to focus on shifting property relations to the present," the professor said.